## The Plague

At the onset of the Third War, the human kingdom of Lordaeon was wracked and devastated by a new, virulent and extremely infectious disease known only as The Plague. No other name was needed. Spreading from infected grain, within days the plague had spread across Lordaeron’s smaller villages and into major population centers. 

While the priests and paladins of Lordaeron attempted to intervene, the many human victims succumbed to the symptoms of nausea, vomiting, pus-filled boils, exhaustion, delirium, and eventually death. It was then that the final symptom showed itself.

In the dead of night, as bodies began to pile up and quarantine measures were started, the infected dead of Lordaeron began to rise again, walking as undead. Still infectious, and now filled with ravenous hunger, the disease-riddled undead began to rip into their own homes, tearing Lordaeron apart from the inside.

From afar, evil minds were satisfied, for the Plague of Undeath had been orchestrated entirely by the Cult of the Damned, a secret cult of necromancers working for the undead Scourge, at the behest of their leader, the necromancer Kel’thuzad. It was crafted for one thing; create bodies for the Scourge’s use.

The plague, an enormous success, has since left Lordaeron a desolate and empty land, its forests blighted and its earth spongy and sick. Nothing grows, and what little lives there lives a sickly, unpleasant life. Undead wander aimlessly in droves, while the remains of the Scourge’s war machines lay rotting in the sun. A kingdom suffering the full brunt of the Scourge’s plague, Lordaeron is a deadplace, where only the dead live.

Its test site proved a success, and so the Scourge has gone on to employ the Plague of Undeath in grand style, and in countless forms across the world.

<br/>

<div style='margin-top:470px;'></div>

***Virulent Strain.*** The Plague of Undeath was crafted by skilled hands under the command of the Lich King, whose overwhelming power over death bolstered the plague’s power. It was one of several strains of blight and death crafted, and was made specifically to facilitate the conversion of living populations into the undead; those killed become extremely easy to revive into undead, while being extremely hard to cure, as well as infectious to a staggering degree. It is deadly only after time has passed for sufficient infection to spread. It is, in other words, a masterpiece, and a marvel of modern science.

***Ascended Lifeforms.*** To the Scourge, few things are more important than finding new ways to deliver the Plague rapidly. In the old days it was grain, but now they are far more direct: canisters of weaponized diseased fluid; undead monsters loaded with exploding infected pus; infected claws and teeth; dragons that breathe infection across the sky; even the land itself is not safe, as the grubs and worms that fester in diseased corpses then burrow underground to spread the infection further. The experimentation of the Scourge upon living and undead creatures never ceases, and neither do the depths of their ingenuity.

***The Blight.*** A late-stage sign of deep, irreversible infection upon an area is called Blight, and it is a sure sign that the undead have chosen a place as base of operations. No longer grassy and live, the very earth has become sick, with spongy soil riddled with worms bursting out, not with grass and trees, but with fungus, a sickly mycelium growing over and choking previous life, and gigantic mushrooms taking their place. A malaise takes over these regions, with a thick mist adding to an atmosphere of terror. Even worse is the sound; these regions are totally silent. Everything is dead. Here, the undead flourish, strengthened by the death in the air. 

