### Disease: Plague of Undeath
While there have been several plagues throughout history, when someone mentions "*the* plague," they are referring to the Plague of Undeath, a deadly necromantic disease that ravaged most of the Eastern Kingdoms during the Third War. 

The Plague affects species differently. The original Plague mostly killed humanoids, causing them to rise as zombies and other undead, while some flora and fauna instead sprouted plague-filled growths. The New Plague developed by certain Forsaken apothecaries could even kill the undead. Other variants have existed, developed in alchemical labs and secret cabals.
 
When a creature is exposed to a source of the plague--such as through breathing spores, eating infested grain, or an open wound--they must make a DC 15 Constitution saving throw, contracting the disease on a failure.
 
It takes 1d4 days for the plague’s symptoms to manifest in an infected creature. Symptoms range from fatigue, nausea, fever, to minor hallucinations. When it manifests, the infected creature suffers one level of exhaustion and regains only half the normal number of hit points from spending Hit Dice and no hit points from finishing a long rest.
 
At the end of each long rest, an infected creature must make a DC 15 Constitution saving throw. On a failed save, the creature gains one level of exhaustion. On a successful save, the creature’s exhaustion level decreases by one level. If a successful saving throw reduces the infected creature’s level of exhaustion below 1, the creature recovers from the disease. 

The plague is resistant to magic. It cannot be cured except by removing exhaustion levels, and immunity to disease only provides advantage on saves against it. If a creature dies from exhaustion while under this disease, necromantic energies infect the body. Every 24 hours it has a 5% chance to rise as an uncontrolled zombie. If *create undead* or similar spells are cast on the corpse, they do not require material components and the created undead remain under the caster's control indefinitely.

<div style='margin-top:-8px;'></div>

### Plagued Template
A living creature who becomes infected by the plague, yet does not perish from it. Typically they are beasts or plants, as most humanoids die from the plague while most constructs, fiends, or undead are unaffected by it. Plagued creatures manifest different symptoms, such as pus-filled sores and open wounds, green or orange coloration, or fungal growths. 

They retain their statistics unless otherwise stated, and gain the following traits. 

***Alignment.*** The plagued creature's alignment is neutral evil.

***Deadly Plague.*** Poison damage that the plagued creature deals ignores resistance and immunity to poison damage. It can inflict the poisoned condition even on creatures normally immune to it. When it deals a critical hit, the target is infected with the plague of undeath.

***Death Burst.*** The plagued creature lets out a burst of toxic sludge when it drops to 0 hit points. Each creature within 5 feet of it must succeed on a DC 15 Constitution saving throw or take 10 (3d6) poison damage and become infected with the plague of undeath on a failed save. A successful save results in half damage and no other effect.

***Attacks.*** When the plagued creature hits with a melee attack, it deals an additional 3 (1d6) poison damage.


